But the artist, whose identity is shrouded in mystery, waded in to the row by writing a letter to Dennis Stinchcombe, who runs the youth club, giving him his 'blessing' to do what he felt was right with the art.

Mr Stinchcombe now says he has had offers in the region of £1 million for the piece - with bidders from across the globe hoping to get their hands on the painting of two lovers entwined in an embrace while checking their mobile phones.

Some art critics have said the man in the painting resembles former Prime Minister Tony Blair.

'We have had big offers from as far away as Beverly Hills,' he said.

'But I am concerned about choosing an appropriate auctioneer and one which is respectful of the work.

